- GREP is your content detector — it reads lines and filters by what's inside them. 
- FIND is your filesystem navigator — it walks directories and filters by metadata (name, size, age, permissions). 
It never looks inside file contents.
- CUT is your column extractor — it slices structured text by delimiter or character position. 
Lightweight but limited to simple single-char delimiters.
- SORT is your ordering engine — lexicographic by default, 
but -n, -h, -V, and -k adapt it to numbers, sizes, versions, and specific fields.
- UNIQ is your duplicate handler — but it only works on adjacent lines, 
so it almost always needs a sort in front of it.
The trio sort | uniq -c | sort -rn is one of the most useful patterns in all of shell scripting.
